<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB REF="8">
<HEAD>TRISTRAM SHANDY.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE &mdash; A CHAMBER, <HI>ornamented with Views of Fortifications, Arms hanging up.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>SHANDY <HI>&s;itting at a Table, large Folios on it</HI>&mdash; TRIM <HI>and</HI> SUSAN <HI>attending.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>WELL, you tell me love has made a a progre&s;s in both their bo&s;oms; but &s;ay, Trim, how does my brother Toby &s;tand the a&s;&s;aults of the widow Wadman?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>An't plea&s;e your honor, he has capitula|ted&mdash;the Captain has taken in love, as he has taken in every thing el&s;e&mdash;he has taken it in like a lamb.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>And the Widow Wadman, I a&s;&s;ure you, Sir, is as far gone as the Captain&mdash;poor gentle|woman! &s;he has taken in love like a lamb too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then mu&s;t we pur&s;ue our &s;cheme&mdash;You mu&s;t continue, Trim, to keep the Captain's flame alive, and you, Su&s;an, mu&s;t lay fre&s;h fuel upon
<PB N="2" REF="9">
the widow's fire; this peace, Trim, will break my poor brother's heart, unle&s;s we get employ|ment for his mind, I have philo&s;ophiz'd with him in vain&mdash;nothing but love can &s;oothe him&mdash;Love, Trim&mdash;mark Su&s;annah&mdash;Love is a pa&s;&s;ion derived from heaven.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, your honor, and it repleni&s;hes the earth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where is my brother?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>An't plea&s;e your honor, he's gone over to the Inn, to vi&s;it poor Lieutenant Lefevre.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I'll go to him&mdash;Trim, drink &s;uc|ce&s;s to the Captain.
<STAGE>(gives money)</STAGE>
If the widow gets this brother of mine, &s;he gets an invaluable trea&s;ure, he has'nt a heart to hurt a fly&mdash;Go, &s;ays he, one day to an overgrown one, which he had caught as it buzz'd about his no&s;e, and torment|ed him cruelly, poor devil, I'll not hurt a hair of thy head. Go, &s;aid he, lifting up the &s;a&s;h, the world is wide enough for thee and me.&mdash;It was a le&s;&s;on which might &s;erve governors and parents better than a whole volume on the &s;ubject of hu|manity
<STAGE>Exit Shandy.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>My ma&s;ter, his honor the captain, and your ma&s;ter his wor&s;hip, Mr. Shandy, could not be match'd in a day's march, Su&s;an;&mdash;good hearts! when the unfortunate claim a&s;&s;i&s;tance, they fling down their money with that &s;pirited jerk of an ho|ne&s;t welcome with which generous &s;ouls only are able to fling down money;&mdash;For each man's &s;or|row they have a tear, for each man's need they have a &s;hilling&mdash;may heaven ever ble&s;s them both.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>La! Mr. Trim, I thought as how you gen|tlemen of the army never pray'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is not half an hour, Su&s;an, &s;ince I heard Lieutenant Lefevre, a &s;oldier, and a brave
<PB N="3" REF="10">
&s;oldier pray devoutly; a &s;oldier, Su&s;an, prays as often of his own accord as a par&s;on; and when he's fighting for his king, and for his country, and for his own life, and for his honor too, he has the mo&s;t rea&s;on to pray to heaven, of any man in the world.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very true, Mr. Trim.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>But when a &s;oldier, my dear girl, has been &s;tanding twelve hours in the trenches&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>A great while to &s;tand indeed, Mr. Trim.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Up to his knees in cold water, or engag'd in long and dangerous marches, harra&s;s'd in his rear to-day, harra&s;&s;ing others to-morrow;&mdash;de|tach'd here,
<STAGE>(wheeling to right)</STAGE>
countermanded there
<STAGE>(wheeling to the left)</STAGE>
re&s;ting this night per|haps upon his arms&mdash;beat up the next in his &s;hirt &mdash;benumb'd in his joints, without &s;traw in his tent to kneel on, he mu&s;t &s;ay his prayers how and when he can.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>And it's my opinion when a &s;oldier gets time to pray, he prays as heartily as any par&s;on of them all, though not with &s;o much fu&s;s and hy|pocri&s;y.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't &s;ay that, Su&s;an; heaven only knows who is hypocrite and who is not; at the great and general review of all, and not till then, it will be &s;een who have de&s;erted from their duty in this world, and who have &s;tood to their po&s;ts, and we &s;hall be advanced accordingly
<STAGE>(&s;tanding up|right.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>And it will never be enquired whether we were flaunting fine ladies, or humble &s;ervant maids.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, &s;weet Su&s;an, nor whether we did our duty in a red coat or a black one.&mdash;But to bu&s;ine&s;s, Su&s;an, the Captain is certainly &s;mitten,
<PB N="4" REF="11">
what marks of love have you perceived in the widow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;he nightly reads over her marriage-&s;ettlement, and every time &s;he reads, cries for her fir&s;t hu&s;band&mdash;a &s;trong &s;ign that &s;he's thinking of a &s;econd.&mdash;But do you know the marks of love, Mr. Trim.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Know them, I have felt them, Su&s;annah,
<STAGE>(pre&s;&s;ing her hand.)</STAGE>
But &s;ay, what do&s;t thou think of love thy&s;elf, my girl?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can tell you what it is through the whole alphabet; par&s;on Yorick taught me. You mu&s;t give me the letter, Mr. Trim, ju&s;t as you give the word of command&mdash;begin with A.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well;&mdash;now mind the word&mdash;take care.
<STAGE>(as he gives the word he exerci&s;es with his &s;tick, and as &s;he an&s;wers, &s;he reckons with the fore-finger of her right hand upon her left hand)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>A!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Agitation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>B!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bewitching.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>C!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Charming.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>D!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Delightful, or dev'li&s;h, which you plea&s;e; in &s;hort, Love is the mo&s;t E&mdash;extravagant, F&mdash; funny, G&mdash;giggli&s;h, H&mdash;humorous, I&mdash;intere&s;ting, K&mdash;O there is no key to it!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>What no key to love, Su&s;annah? O there is a key!&mdash;Well, go on.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Love is the mo&s;t L&mdash;longing, M&mdash;mi&s;|guiding, N&mdash;natural, O&mdash;the O expre&s;&s;es its own meaning, its the &s;ame with the heigh-ho!
<STAGE>(&s;ighs)</STAGE>
P&mdash;plea&s;ant, Q.&mdash;quarrel&s;ome, R&mdash;rapturous&mdash; but here comes Obadiah, &s;o the next time we
<PB N="5" REF="12">
meet, I'll give you the S, T, U, W, X, Y, and Z, of love.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>With the <HI>et caetera,</HI> I hope, Su&s;an&mdash;for the <HI>et caetera</HI> is worth the whole alphabet.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> OBADIAH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oba.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! alas! Corporal! as &s;ure as I'm alive, the poor Lieutenant at the inn will die&mdash;and yet he was better this morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(<HI>&s;tanding in the middle.</HI>)</STAGE>
Alas!
<STAGE>(<HI>extending his right arm</HI>)</STAGE>
What is this morning, or any other morning, to the time pre&s;ent?&mdash;Are we not here now&mdash;
<STAGE>(<HI>&s;etting his &s;tick perpendicular</HI>)</STAGE>
and are we not gone in a moment?
<STAGE>Dropping his hat.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>O yes, gone in a moment.
<STAGE>Weeps.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>I own, that &s;ince the morning it is not long till now, it is nothing; but to tho&s;e, Oba|diah, who know not what death is, and what havoc and de&s;truction he can make before a man can wheel about,
<STAGE>(<HI>wheeling.</HI>)</STAGE>
it is a whole age.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oba.</SPEAKER>
<P>How learnedly the Corporal preaches.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Obadiah! O Su&s;annah! it would make a good natur'd man's heart bleed, to con|&s;ider, how many a brave upright fellow hath been laid low &s;ince that time&mdash;Tru&s;t me, Su&s;an, before that time comes again, many a bright eye will be dim.
<STAGE>Points to Su&s;an's eye.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Mr. Trim, many a bright eye will be dim.
<STAGE>Curt&s;ies and rubs her eyes.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are we not like the flower of the field?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Looking at Su&s;an.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, we are like the flowers of the field.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Smiles.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is not all fle&s;h gra&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Looking at Obadiah.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oba.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;all fle&s;h is gra&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="6" REF="13">
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis clay, 'tis dirt&mdash;
<STAGE>(<HI>points to Obadiah.</HI>)</STAGE>
&mdash;What is the fine&s;t face that a man ever look'd on?
<STAGE>pointing to Su&s;an.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>I could hear Trim talk for ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is the fine&s;t face
<STAGE>(<HI>taps Su&s;an's cheek, &s;he lays her hand up<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">n his &s;houlder and &s;miles.</HI>)</STAGE>
What is it but corruption?
<STAGE>(<HI>&s;he takes away her hand.</HI>)</STAGE>
&mdash;Out of doors I value not death at all, not this&mdash;
<STAGE>(<HI>&s;napping his fingers.</HI>)</STAGE>
&mdash;Let him not take me cowardly, what is he? a pull of a trigger, a pu&s;h of a bayonet. The be&s;t way is to &s;tand up to him, the man who flies, is in ten times more danger, than he who marches up to his jaws. I have look'd him an hundred times in his face.&mdash; Death is nothing in the field.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oba.</SPEAKER>
<P>But he's woundedly frightful in the hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>For my part, I think it's mo&s;t natural to meet him in bed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>And could I e&s;cape him in bed, by creeping into the wor&s;t calf-&s;kin that ever was made into a knap&s;ack, I'd do it there&mdash;but that is nature.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oba.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I mu&s;t go &s;ee after the &s;ick cow, tho' I could hear the corporal for ever.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit Obadiah.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's Captain Shandy fears not death, he fears only what every hone&s;t man fears&mdash;doing a wrong thing. He's as kind an officer as ever &s;tepp'd before a platoon, and would march up to the muzzle of a cannon, tho' there were a light|ed match at the touch-hole. He'll take care of Lefevre's &s;on&mdash;I'd &s;erve him to the day of my death for love.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I'd &s;ooner be his &s;ervant for &s;even pounds a year, than &s;erve other people for eight.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="7" REF="14">
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank thee for thy twenty &s;hillings a year, as much, Su&s;an, as if thou putte&s;t the mo|ney into my own pocket. I mu&s;t ki&s;s thee for it, Su&s;an.
<STAGE>Ki&s;&s;es her.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> OBADIAH, (<HI>calling.</HI>)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oba.</SPEAKER>
<P>Su&s;ay! Su&s;an! Su&s;annah! you are call'd for here, call'd for there, call'd for every where! there's mi&s;tre&s;s taken woundedly&punc; ill, Jane is &s;ent for the midwife, and Jerry for Mrs. Wadman, and I mu&s;t gallop for Dr. Slop&mdash;But what bea&s;t &s;hall I take? The coach-hor&s;e wants a &s;hoe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't take him, poor creature.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oba.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Scotch hor&s;e is gall'd, and can't bear a &s;addle upon his back.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Take Patriot, Obadiah.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oba.</SPEAKER>
<P>Patriot! ah Su&s;an! no&mdash;poor Patriot's &s;old! Well, I'll e'en borrow the miller's cart-hor&s;e, or walk, for better to walk thro' thick and thin all the days of a man's life, than to ride a poor un&s;hod devil, or a devil with a gall'd back, that mu&s;t feel pain every inch of the road&mdash;But I forgot, ma&s;ter's returned from the inn, and would &s;peak with you, Mr. Trim.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Farewell, Su&s;an, when the widow comes remember your ma&s;ter's in&s;tructions&mdash;Su&s;an, we mu&s;t all marry.
<STAGE>Exit Trim and Obadiah.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, 'tis twenty to one but mi&s;tre&s;s dies this bout&mdash;poor gentlewoman, &s;he has always had a hard time, and &s;he has as good cloaths as any lady in the county, and ma&s;ter would give them all to me no doubt.
<STAGE>(<HI>bell rings.</HI>)</STAGE>
Coming! Her green &s;attin is va&s;tly pretty, green becomes my complexion, yes, I was always fond of a green gown,
<STAGE>(<HI>rings.</HI>)</STAGE>
why coming! then her red dama&s;k &s;tands an end,
<STAGE>(<HI>rings.</HI>)</STAGE>
coming! and &s;he has an
<PB N="8" REF="15">
orange tawny armozine, a white padua, and a yellow lute&s;tring, be&s;ides a world of linen, bed|gowns, laces, and comfortable under-petticoats.
<STAGE>(<HI>rings.</HI>)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SHANDY <HI>and</HI> TRIM, <HI>as</HI> SUSAN <HI>goes out.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why Su&s;an, Su&s;an, they are calling for you all over the hou&s;e&mdash;away, my girl, away.
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit Su&s;an.</HI>)</STAGE>
Should the Lieutenant die, Trim, 'twould go to my brother's heart, &s;o let's pur&s;ue our &s;cheme again&s;t him and the widow with all expedition.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>And plea&s;e your honor, I fear I &s;hall want &s;pirits.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, Trim, never be grave&mdash;gravity is an errant &s;coundrel, and of the mo&s;t dangerous kind too&mdash;becau&s;e a &s;ly one; more hone&s;t, well meaning people are bubbled out of their goods and monies by gravity in a twelve-month, than by poc|ket picking and &s;hop-lifting in &s;even years. Here comes my brother, I'll &s;tep into the library to overlook my catalogue of chri&s;tian names, but will come out if I &s;ee occa&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CAPTAIN SHANDY <HI>on a Crutch,</HI> TRIM <HI>hands a Chair,</HI> TOBY <HI>&s;its.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have &s;een the Lieutenant, Trim, he is the &s;ame Lefevre who &s;erv'd at Angus's at Breda, and who&s;e wife was unfortunately kill'd by a mu&s;ket ball, as &s;he lay in his arms in his tent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>I remember the &s;tory an't plea&s;e your honor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then well may the poor Lieutenant remember it&mdash;when you waited on the Lieute|nant, and made him an offer of my &s;ervices, did
<PB N="9" REF="16">
you offer him my pur&s;e?&mdash;Sickne&s;s and travel|ling are both expen&s;ive, and thou knowe&s;t he was a poor Lieutenant, with a &s;on to &s;ub&s;i&s;t as well as him&s;elf out of his pay&mdash;Thou &s;hould'&s;t have made him an offer of my pur&s;e, becau&s;e if he &s;tood in need, Trim, thou knowe&s;t he had been as welcome to it as my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your honor knows I had no orders.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>True,
<STAGE>(<HI>ri&s;ing.</HI>)</STAGE>
thou had'&s;t not orders, and thou did'&s;t very right, Trim, as a &s;oldier, but very ill as a man.
<STAGE>(<HI>&s;its, Trim bows.</HI>)</STAGE>
Then when thou offered&s;t whatever was in my hou&s;e, thou &s;hould'&s;t have offered him my hou&s;e too.
<STAGE>(<HI>Trim bows.</HI>)</STAGE>
A &s;ick brother officer &s;hould have the be&s;t quarters, Trim, and what with my care, and thy care, and the old woman's care, and his boy's care, we might recruit him again, and &s;et him on his legs.
<STAGE>(<HI>ri&s;es.</HI>)</STAGE>
In a fortnight or three weeks he might march.</P>
<STAGE>Putting forward his right leg.</STAGE>
<P><HI>Shandy, peeping.</HI> Precious &s;ouls! what are their two noddles together about?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>He will never march, an't plea&s;e your honor, in this world.
<STAGE>Drawing back his left leg.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>He will march.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>A'nt plea&s;e your honor, he will never march but to the grave.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;hall march to his regiment.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Rai&s;es his crutch.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>He cannot &s;tand it, your honor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;hall be &s;upported.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Leans on his crutch.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>He will drop at la&s;t, and what will be|come of his boy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;hall not drop.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, well aday! do what we can for him, the poor &s;oul will die.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="10" REF="17">
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;hall not die by&mdash;heaven!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't &s;wear, your honor.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>SHANDY <HI>comes forward.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your hand, brother&mdash;the accu&s;ing &s;pirit which flew up to heaven's chancery with thy oath, blu&s;h'd as he gave it in, and the recording angel, as he wrote it down, dropp'd a tear upon the word, that blotted it out for ever.&mdash;But con&s;ider, dear Toby, all mu&s;t die! monarchs, princes, dance in the &s;ame ring with us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has the widow been here, Trim?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Kingdoms and provinces, towns and cities, have they not their period? when tho&s;e principles and powers which fir&s;t put them to|gether&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>Brother brother,
<STAGE>(<HI>laying his hand upon his brea&s;t.</HI>)</STAGE>
I hope you except this country from your principles and powers, there was no princi|ple in the powers which oppo&s;e her, and &s;he has now principle and power &s;ufficient within her&s;elf, to keep her firm upon her own broad ba&s;is.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, an't plea&s;e your honor, and having ju&s;tice on her &s;ide, &s;he's able to drive France and Spain and&mdash;and the devil if he &s;hould join them, out of the field.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>The approaches of death, Toby, make but little alteration in a great man&mdash;Ve&s;pa&s;ian died in a je&s;t, Galba with a &s;entence, Septimus Severus with a di&s;patch, Tiberius with di&s;&s;imula|tion, and Cae&s;ar Augu&s;tus with a compliment.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Capt. whi&s;tles Lillibullero.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope your honor, it was a &s;incere one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was to his wife, Trim&mdash;but la&s;tly comes the anecdote, which, like the gilded dome,
<PB N="11" REF="18">
crowns in all&mdash;never did man receive &s;uch &s;evere la&s;hes as Cornelius Gallus.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>The greate&s;t number of la&s;hes I ever &s;aw given, was to a grenadier in Mackay's regiment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>O heav'ns! he was innocent, yet he was flogg'd to death's door, they had better &s;hot him outright, as he begg'd, and he'd have gone to heaven directly.
<STAGE>Weeps.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was a misfortune, great as ever the eye of pity dropp'd a tear on&mdash;it would be a pity, Trim, thou &s;hould'&s;t ever feel &s;orrows of thy own, thou feel'&s;t &s;o tenderly for others&mdash;But whil&s;t thy ma&s;ter has a &s;hilling, thou &s;halt not a&s;k el&s;ewhere for a penny.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>DR. SLOP <HI>without.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>Scoundrel, I wi&s;h you hang'd, I wi&s;h you &s;hot.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>This cur&s;ing, Dr. Slop, is no more than &s;parrow &s;hot fired again a ba&s;tion. Our armies &s;wore terribly in Flanders, Doctor, but nothing to this&mdash;My heart would not let me cur&s;e the de|vil with &s;o much bitterne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>The devil's damn'd already to all eter|nity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor devil,
<STAGE>(<HI>&s;ighs.</HI>)</STAGE>
I'm &s;orry for him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>That ra&s;cal, Obadiah, has injur'd me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oba.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Doctor, I would not injure a toad from my heart, and I's no ra&s;cal, and I &s;corn a lie&mdash;I met Mr. Doctor, an't plea&s;e you, coming &s;lowly along, waddling thro' the dirt, at a duck's gait, upon his little poney, the poor bea&s;t &s;carce able to &s;et foot to ground under its heavy burden, for the Doctor is a mortal load of human fle&s;h, as you mon &s;ee&mdash;he! he! he!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="19">
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who do you laugh at, Sirrah? I was com|ing to pay my devoirs to the widow Wadman, not knowing of your lady's alarm, when this fellow came po&s;ting down the narrow lane, at a mon|&s;trous and tremendous rate, mounted on a huge cart hor&s;e, prick'd into a full gallop.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oba.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was the miller's old troop hor&s;e, and 'tis as good natur'd a bea&s;t&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>As your&s;elf, Sirrah,&mdash;you came &s;pla&s;h|ing and plunging like a devil thro' thick and thin, a phenomenon with a vortex of mud and water round its axis&mdash;What mu&s;t be my terror and hy|drophobia, when advancing warily in an ambling motion, this Obadiah and his miller's troop hor&s;e, turns a corner furious, pop full upon me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oba.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Doctor, you were in fault, for you looked round when I cried out to you to hold the pummel of the &s;addle, and in looking round you let go your whip, and attempting to &s;ave your whip, you lo&s;t your &s;eat.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>And when the Doctor lo&s;t his &s;eat, he lo&s;t his pre&s;ence of mind.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oba.</SPEAKER>
<P>And before I was near him, your honor, he fell from his poney, for all the world like a pack of wool, quite at his ea&s;e, with the broader part of him &s;unk in the mud twelve inches.
<STAGE>Laughs.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>You're an ill-manner'd knave.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oba.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, as to my manners, did'nt I pull off my hat twice, once when your wor&s;hip was falling,
<STAGE>(laughs)</STAGE>
and again when I &s;aw you in the mud?
<STAGE>Laughs.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SUSAN.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>My poor mi&s;tre&s;s is ready to faint! and the drops are &s;pilt, and the bottle of julip is broken, the nur&s;e has cut her arm, and the mid|wife
<PB N="13" REF="20">
has fall'n upon the fender, and bruis'd her hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>If the midwife's hip be bruis'd, it is fitting I &s;hould go look at it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Doctor, I reque&s;t your immediate attendance on Mrs. Shandy&mdash;Obadiah will pull off your boots, and &s;upply you with a pair of &s;lip|pers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>And had I my will, Obadiah &s;hould be &s;upplied with a halter.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt Su&s;an, Slop, and Obadiah.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan</SPEAKER>
<P>I am convinc'd, Toby, that Mrs. Shandy will have a boy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>The widow Wadman, brother, is before my eyes day and night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;on's name &s;hall be Tri&s;megi&s;tus.
<STAGE>(Trim peeps in.)</STAGE>
Who's there?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(<HI>half in.</HI>)</STAGE>
It is nothing, an't plea&s;e your honor, but two mortars.
<STAGE>In a low voice.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>They &s;han't make a clatter with their mortars here&mdash;If Dr. Slop has any drugs to pound, let him do it in the kitchen.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>May it plea&s;e your honor, they are two mortar pieces for a &s;iege, which I have been making
<STAGE>(comes on with a pair of jack boots in his hand.)</STAGE>
out of a pair of jack boots, which Obadiah told me, your honor had left off wearing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(<HI>taking a boot.</HI>)</STAGE>
By heav'n! I have not one appointment belonging to me, which I &s;et &s;o much &s;tore by, as I do by the&s;e jack-boots.&mdash; They were our grandfather's, Toby, they were hereditary.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(<HI>taking the other boot.</HI>)</STAGE>
Then I fear, Trim has cut off the entail.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cut off the tail!&mdash;no, plea&s;e your honor,
<STAGE>(taking the boot from Toby.)</STAGE>
I have only cut off the top.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="14" REF="21">
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hate perpetuities as much as any man alive, Toby; but the&s;e boots were worn by Sir Roger Shandy, at the battle of Mar&s;ton Moor&mdash; I would not have taken ten pounds for them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll pay you the money, brother, with all my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Trim, &s;tep into the kitchen, and enquire how things go on up &s;tairs,
<STAGE>(<HI>exit Trim.</HI>)</STAGE>
Brother Toby, you care not what money you throw away, provided it is upon a &s;iege&mdash;Dear Toby, the&s;e military operations are above your &s;trength, and will in the end quite ruin and make a beggar of you.&mdash;What's your modern artillery, to the bat|tering rams of the ancients, to the catapulta&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> TRIM.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>An't plea&s;e your honor, there is no one &s;oul in the kitchen, except Dr. Slop.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Some retrogade planet is hanging over this hou&s;e of mine, turning every thing out of its place&mdash;I thought the Doctor had been with Mrs. Shandy! what can he be puzzling about in the kitchen?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's buzy, an't plea&s;e your honor, in making a bridge.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>It's very obliging in him&mdash;Pray give my humble &s;ervice to Dr. Slop, and tell him I thank him heartily&mdash;He's making his bridge, I &s;uppo&s;e, after the model of the Marquis de Ho&s;pitals.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven ble&s;s your honor! it's a bridge for young ma&s;ter's no&s;e.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Confu&s;ion!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam has got a &s;on, but Dr. Slop, as Su&s;an told me on the &s;tair head, has cru&s;h'd his no&s;e as flat as a pancake, and is making a fal&s;e
<PB N="15" REF="22">
bridge with a piece of cotton, and a bit of whale|bone to rai&s;e it up.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lead me, brother Toby, lead me to my room this in&s;tant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Keep up your &s;pirits&mdash;Meet me pre&s;ently in the bowling-green with the mortars, Trim..</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cru&s;h'd his no&s;e! O heaven&mdash;O unfortu|nate mutilated child.</P>
</SP>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB REF="23">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE <HI>a Room.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>WIDOW WADMAN <HI>and</HI> SUSAN.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Widow.</SPEAKER>
<P>AND are you convinc'd, Su&s;an, that Capt. Shandy intends paying his ad|dre&s;&s;es to me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Madam, the Captain is as mild as new milk, and Trim &s;ays, he loves you better than gun-powder, yet indeed, Madam, he is &s;o mode&s;t a gentleman, that you mu&s;t c<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">urt him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>And you'll &s;ound the Corporal upon what I have &s;poken to you, you know the Captain has been wounded, and one would not wi&s;h to turn nur&s;e, and marry a patient&mdash;Here comes the Corporal, &s;o remember your bu&s;ine&s;s.
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I'll di&s;cover every thing for this poor widow, I'll &s;erve her, for &s;he has really made me a genteel pre&s;ent&mdash;perhaps this is her la&s;t &s;take, &s;o I'll cut the cards cautiou&s;ly, and who knows but hearts may turn up trumps.
<STAGE>(enter Trim.)</STAGE>
La, Mr. Trim, is it true that the Captain can never recover his wound?&mdash;Dr. Slop &s;ays he cannot.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my life, Su&s;an, the Doctor's in|&s;inuations are as fal&s;e as hell&mdash;but why do'&s;t thou a&s;k? thou art good and mode&s;t by nature, and &s;o generous a girl, thou would'&s;t not wound an in&s;ect, much le&s;s the honor of &s;o
<PB N="17" REF="24">
worthy and gallant a &s;oul as my ma&s;ter&mdash;Thou ha&s;t been &s;et on and deluded, Su&s;an, as is often a woman's ca&s;e, to plea&s;e others more than them|&s;elves, who&s;e &s;u&s;picion has mi&s;led thee&mdash;Tell me, for by my Montero cap I love thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you really love me? To be &s;ure, you &s;oldiers are the cleane&s;t, neate&s;t, uprighte&s;t men&mdash;and indeed Mr. Trim, I always liked you, and will tell you the truth&mdash;I was &s;et on to make my enquiries by the widow Wadman&mdash;Here comes the Captain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Su&s;an, meet me pre&s;ently at the fortifications, and I'll &s;hew you our new Dutch bridge.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall not fail&mdash;but you men are not to be tru&s;ted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, 'tis you women are not to be tru&s;ted&mdash;Always changing your appearances, and, con&s;idering the changes of life, there is no an&s;wering for one of you a moment&mdash;Some grow out like pumkins, and lo&s;e their &s;hape&mdash;Others go off like flowers, and lo&s;e their beauty&mdash;Nay, &s;weet Su&s;an, how many go off like hu&s;&s;eys, and lo&s;e them&s;elves?
<STAGE>Exit Su&s;an.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> TOBY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>I believe, your honor, I am going to &s;ay a fooli&s;h kind of a thing for a &s;oldier.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;oldier, Trim, is no more exempt from &s;aying fooli&s;h things, than a man of let|ters.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>But a &s;oldier, your honor, does not &s;ay fooli&s;h things &s;o often as a man of letters&mdash;Since the peace, your honor, I have never once whi&s;tled,
<PB N="18" REF="25">
nor laughed, nor cried, nor talk'd of pa&s;t done deeds, nor told your honor a good nor a bad &s;tory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have remark'd it, Trim.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then &s;ince the war is over, your honor, we &s;hould look for other employment&mdash;We have wounded the widow Wadman, and I believe, your honor, &s;he has returned the fire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>She has attacked my brea&s;t works from the battery of her eyes, and has left a ball here.
<STAGE>Pointing to his heart.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your honor mu&s;t attack her in return&mdash; &s;he can no more &s;tand a &s;iege than &s;he can fly&mdash; we'll get your honor's regimentals bru&s;hed up, and I'll put your ramilie wig in pipes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>And get &s;ome chalk for my &s;word.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>It will be in your honor's way&mdash;but when your honor is &s;haved, and your clean &s;hirt on, and every thing ready for the attack, we will match up to the widow, as boldly as to the face of a ba&s;tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>I declare, Corporal, I'd rather march up to the edge of a Trench&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Trench, your honor! a woman is quite a different thing&mdash;But I mu&s;t retire, your honor, for here comes the widow, running down the gallery like one bewitched&mdash;We &s;hould never have fallen in love but for the peace.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MRS. WADMAN, (<HI>running.</HI>)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Widow.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am half di&s;tracted, Capt. Shandy, a mote or &s;and, or &s;omething has got into this
<PB N="19" REF="26">
eye of mine&mdash;For pity's &s;weet &s;ake, look at it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>I prote&s;t, Madam, I can &s;ee nothing&mdash;
<STAGE>(<HI>looks with a gla&s;s.</HI>)</STAGE>
Nothing can I &s;ee, but the eye it&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is it not in the white, Captain, look into it again?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>As I am a &s;oldier, Mrs. Wadman, it is in vain, I have reconnoitered every corner, and can &s;ee nothing, Widow&mdash;but fire!&mdash;fire!&mdash; &s;hooting from every part.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is ea&s;y now&mdash;well, the eye is the mo&s;t tender part about us&mdash;and the mo&s;t orna|mental.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>And the mo&s;t dangerous, Madam&mdash;an eye is for all the world, in this re&s;pect, ex|actly like a cannon, that it is not &s;o much the eye nor the cannon them&s;elves, as it is the car|riage of the eye and the carriage of the cannon, by which both the one and the other are enabled to do &s;o much execution&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then there are many kinds of eyes&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, widow, and many kinds of can|non.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>The rolling eye&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>And the battering cannon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>The commanding eye&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>And the field piece.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>The langui&s;hing eye&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>And the howitzer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>The forbidding eye&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>And the horn petard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>The imperious eye&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Of all eyes, good Heaven! defend me from the imperious one&mdash;There are more evils in &s;uch an eye, widow, than in a whole train of ar|tillery
<PB N="20" REF="27">
&mdash;
<STAGE>(<HI>She gives him her hand.</HI>)</STAGE>
O give me, Mrs. Wadman, an eye full of gentle &s;alutations and &s;oft notes, whi&s;pering like the la&s;t low accents of a dying &s;aint.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee, Captain, you are acquainted with the &s;oft pa&s;&s;ions of love as well as the hor|rors of war&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>War, Madam! What is war? But get|ting together a number of quiet and harmle&s;s people with &s;words in their hands, to keep the turbulent and ambitious within bounds&mdash;It is one thing to gather laurels, it is another to &s;cat|ter cypre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stop, Captain&mdash;You are &s;o gallant, &s;o ardent, I wonder a gentleman of your figure could &s;o long have lived comfortably alone, with|out a bo&s;om to re&s;t your head on, or tru&s;t your cares to. But then that dreadful wound&mdash;where did you receive it, Captain?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;hall &s;ee, Madam, the very &s;pot where I&mdash;
<STAGE>(<HI>pulls out a plan.</HI>)</STAGE>
Ju&s;t here, Madam, before the gate of St. Nicholas, in one of the traver&s;es of the French, oppo&s;ite to the &s;alient angle of the demi ba&s;tion of St. Roch&mdash;I &s;up|po&s;e you under&s;tand the geography of the place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>A fig for the geography&mdash;We were &s;peaking of love and matrimony.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>But mu&s;t po&s;tpone the conver&s;ation, &s;weet widow, for here comes my brother.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>What an interruption!
<STAGE>(<HI>a&s;ide.</HI>)</STAGE>
Well, Captain, I &s;hall take a view of your fortifications, as &s;oon as I pay a &s;hort vi&s;it to poor Mrs. Shandy.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB REF="28"><HI>Enter</HI> SHANDY, <HI>walking &s;olemnly in his Night Gown, Slippers, and Cap&mdash;a large Folio under his Arm.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hem&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>We &s;hould be over&s;et and torn to pieces an hundred times a day, brother Toby, was it not for a &s;ecret &s;pring within us&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Which &s;pring I take to be religion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will that &s;et my boy's no&s;e on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Religion, brother, makes every thing &s;trait.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Since the greate&s;t evil has befallen him, I mu&s;t counteract and undo it with the greate&s;t good&mdash;His name &s;hall &s;ave him&mdash;He &s;hall be baptized Tri&s;megi&s;tus.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h his long name may an&s;wer for his &s;hort no&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is a name will bring all things to rights. This Tri&s;megi&s;tus was the greate&s;t of all earthly beings&mdash;He was the greate&s;t king, the greate&s;t philo&s;opher, the greate&s;t prie&s;t&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>And engineer, I &s;uppo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>No doubt, brother, he was an engineer, as he was a prie&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SUSAN.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>The child is dying, Sir, dying&mdash;but the curate is in the dre&s;&s;ing room, waiting for the name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's as black in the face as my&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>What&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why my &s;hoe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>He is to be called Tri&s;megi&s;tus.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="22" REF="29">
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can'&s;t thou carry Tri&s;megi&s;tus in thy head acro&s;s the gallery without forgetting.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Sits and buttons his knees.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can I!&mdash;Tri&s;&mdash;tri&s;&mdash;tri&s;&mdash;gi&s;tus&mdash;gi&s;tus.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Of all the puzzling riddles in the mar|ried &s;tate, brother Toby, there is not one that has more intricacies in it than this&mdash;That from the moment the mi&s;tre&s;s of the hou&s;e is brought to bed, every female in it, from the lady's gentle|woman down to the cinder wench, become an inch taller, and give them&s;elves more airs on that &s;ingle inch, than on all their other inches put to|gether&mdash;Now we'll go &s;ee Tri&s;megi&s;tus&punc;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> TRIM.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>The child is chri&s;tened, and plea&s;e your honor&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>And Su&s;annah has not forgot the name.
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SUSAN (<HI>crying.</HI>)</STAGE></P>
<P>What's the matter, Su&s;an?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>No body is in fault but Mr. Yorick's cu|rate&mdash;I ran all the way calling over the name, and told him it was Tri&s;tramgi&s;tus</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>She did, indeed&punc; your honor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>He called me noodle, and &s;aid there was no gi&s;tus in it, and chri&s;tened my young ma&s;ter, Tri&s;tram, which he &s;aid was his own name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shand.</SPEAKER>
<P>Retire&mdash;
<STAGE>(<HI>pu&s;hes her out.</HI>)</STAGE>
fire! fury! women! and wind!&mdash;Unhappy Tri&s;tram&mdash;Child of decripitude&mdash;What misfortune or di&s;a&s;ter in
<PB N="23" REF="30">
the book of amylratic evils, which could un|mechanize thy frame, which has not fallen upon thy head?
<STAGE>Going.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was all owing, an't plea&s;e your honor, to Su&s;an's mi&s;take&mdash;it was her error, not a fault.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Trim, thou wer't ever a friend to the di&s;tre&s;&s;ed&mdash;And a true friend, for thou ha&s;t a&s;|&s;i&s;ted them behind their backs&mdash;I have left, Trim, my Bowling-green brother&mdash;I have left him a pen&s;ion! he always obeyed orders, whether from his officer or from Heaven.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Had Count Solmes done the &s;ame at the battle of Steenkirk, Trim, it would have &s;aved thee from having been run over by the dragoons.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Peevi&s;hly.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sav'd me! your honor, it would have &s;aved five battalions!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Trim's right! perfectly right!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Count Solmes &s;hould have &s;ent up the foot, not the hor&s;e&mdash;We would have fired with them muzzle to muzzle for their lives&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Tri&s;tram!
<STAGE>(<HI>wringing his hand.</HI>)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>The French, brother; had the advantage of a wood; and give them a moment's time to re|trench them&s;elves, they are a nation will pop, and pop at you for ever&mdash;There is no way but to march cooly up to them, receive their fire, and fall upon them&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pell, mell&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ding dong&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hor&s;e and foot&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Helter &s;kelter&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Right and left&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Front and flank&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sword in hand&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="24" REF="31">
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Blood and 'ouns&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Both.</SPEAKER>
<P>Huzza!&mdash;huzza!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt Toby and Trim.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven! how the battle rages! But is not a man's Hobby-hor&s;e the tendere&s;t part about him&mdash;and why &s;hould I hurt a brother's? I'll &s;end the Widow Wadman to him this in|&s;tant, &s;he mu&s;t put an end to this brother's mili|tary frenzy&mdash;O Tri&s;tram! Tri&s;tram!
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE>SCENE, <HI>a</HI> HEDGE <HI>acro&s;s the Stage, with a Gate.&mdash;A Centry Box and Garden Chair on one &s;ide, on the other the Ruins of a Fortification&mdash; a Draw-Bridge, and &s;everal Pioneers In&s;truments on the Stage.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> TRIM <HI>with a Spade.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o our fortifications are de&s;troyed &mdash;Well I'll throw the implements into the bar|row and roll them off the field.
<STAGE>(<HI>&s;ighs</HI>)</STAGE>
No, I'll do it before his honor ri&s;es in the morning &mdash;He took plea&s;ure in them and to &s;ee them removed might give him pain&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SUSAN.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>La, Mr. Trim, what dreadful havoc you have made with your fortifications&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here &s;tood the ba&s;tion, and here were the ravelins, and there lay the French&mdash;and here was the gate of St. Nicholas, where his ho|nor received his wound.&mdash;Thy crying, Su&s;an, hath made thee look charming&mdash;thou look'&s;t like the moi&s;t eye of an April morn!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="25" REF="32">
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do believe you love me, Trim&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and we'll marry, Su&s;an&mdash;We'll marry &mdash;The peace will make us all marry!&mdash; But here comes the Captain, &s;o get behind the draw-bridge, and I will come to thee pre&s;ently, and tell thee a &s;tory I promi&s;ed&mdash;of the King of Bohemia and his &s;even ca&s;tles.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I'll wait, for I would not for the world be taken in confu&s;ion by the Captain.
<STAGE>(<HI>goes behind the bridge.</HI>)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> TOBY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think, an't plea&s;e your honour, that the fortifications are almo&s;t de&s;troyed, and the ba&s;on is upon a level with the mole&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then there is no further occa&s;ion for our &s;ervices&mdash;But, Trim, the widow has promi&s;ed to meet me here immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Does &s;he know any thing of your ho|nor's being in love?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven help her, no more than the child unborn.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! your honor, &s;he does&mdash;I know women, and have ob&s;erved the widow's bu&s;h-firing from behind the yew hedge.&mdash;Well, I'll &s;tand centinel behind the bridge, and give your honor notice if any one approaches
<STAGE>(goes behind the bridge.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> WIDOW WADMAN.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;ee, Captain, I am punctual to my appointment&mdash;La! you can't think what I have
<PB N="26" REF="33">
been meditating on&mdash;But what is your opinion, Captain Shandy? Are not the cares and anxiety of the marriage &s;tate very great?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;uppo&s;e &s;o&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>You can have no inclination for chang|ing your &s;tate;&mdash;Indeed I can &s;ee no rea&s;on for a man's marrying&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SLOP.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, madam, you'll &s;ee a very good rea&s;on written in the law of Mo&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>This intru&s;ion, Dr. Slop,
<STAGE>(he retreats, &s;he follows.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are not children the very end of the in&s;titution.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>A fiddle &s;tick!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stop.</SPEAKER>
<P>She wants you to marry her, Captain Shandy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis fal&s;e
<STAGE>(<HI>Slop retreats, the Widow fol|lowing, till they throw down the bridge, and di&s;|cover Trim and Su&s;an &s;itting behind it.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy defend us!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! Madam Lucretia, have we caught you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>I told you, Trim, that bed-cords would never be &s;ufficient to &s;ecure the bridge if attack|ed by cavalry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was a Dutch bridge, your honor, and &s;o there was no depending on it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>He was &s;hewing it to me, he! he! he!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>And in the proof of its excellency and
<PB N="27" REF="34">
&s;trength &s;ome how or other the captain's bridge has been broken down, he! he! he!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was all a misfortune-&s;hewing Su&s;an the &s;pot where his honour got his wound, and going too near the edge of the fo&s;&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>You unfortunately &s;lipped in&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>And having Su&s;an under the arm.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Su&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>He dragged me in after him, he! he! he!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>By means of which, Su&s;an fell back|wards &s;o&s;s again&s;t the bridge, and my foot get|ting into the curvette, I fell forward full again&s;t the bridge too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>And pray, pretty madam, how do you intend to repair your reputation?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who dare injure her reputation?&mdash;She has a &s;oldier to protect her&mdash;he who injures the character of a woman is a villain, and a coward in his heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Slop.</SPEAKER>
<P>That may be&mdash;but I'll make an inci&s;ion in her character.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Widow, will you marry me?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SHANDY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Marry, brother!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Toby.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I wi&s;h to marry the widow with all my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>And the widow has not the heart to re|fu&s;e you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Trim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your honour has carried the place by <HI>coup de main.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou art a true daughter of Eve&mdash;Well, Toby, thou wilt never lie diagonally in thy bed
<PB N="28" REF="35">
again!
<STAGE>(<HI>joins their hands</HI>)</STAGE>
and &s;ince peace is now e&s;tabli&s;hed, I hope every unmarried man and &s;ingle woman will follow the example of you and the widow, and encrea&s;e the &s;trength of the nation by rai&s;ing &s;upplies for the next war.</P>
</SP>
</DIV2>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
</DIV1>
